  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Coffee for a Living Income</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Many coffee farmers and producers across the world live in poverty, the global coffee prices are often not high enough to earn a living income. Trabocca, Simon L&#xE9;velt and Fairfood share the vision that everyone involved in the production of our food should earn a living income/living wage. Trabocca and Fairfood started a pilot last year which led to promising results on traceable coffee but also showed us a lot of data on incomes is missing to understand the depth of the problem.In this project we will trace the supply chains and analyse the price gap that contributes to earning a living income. The suppliers in this project represent 9% of Trabocca&#x2019;s annual purchase value (2019). This project is thus addressing a significant part of Trabocca&#x2019;s supply chain value and will make a serious impact on the ground.Phase A of the project will run from 2021 to 2022, in which we benchmark a living income and the cost of production for the Guji region in Ethiopia. Certain trusted organisations are specialised in conducting research and publishing living wage and income benchmarks, like the Global Living Wage Coalition and the Living Income Community of Practice. One of the most widely accepted methodologies for calculating a living wage or income is the Anker methodology. After comparing this with pricing paid, phase B will focus on how to close the income gap and how to potentially increase our reach beyond the initial two Ethiopian partners.</narrative>
  </description>
